en, unabhängig von der Art der benutzten Schnittstellen und der Technologie.  aExisting Online Public Access Catalogues (OPACs) demonstrate differences in the range and complexity of their functional features, terminology, and help facilities. While many libraries already have OPACs, there is a need to bring together, in the form of guidelines or recommendations, a corpus of good practice to assist libraries in designing or re-designing the displays for their OPACs, taking into consideration the needs of users. The audience for these guidelines is librarians charged with customizing OPAC software and vendors and producers of this software. The guidelines are mainly designed for general libraries with collections of resources in the humanities, the social sciences, and the pure and applied sciences. The guidelines are intended to apply to any type of catalogue, independently of the kind of interface and technology used.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aLibrary catalogs. 0aOnline library catalogs. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Library & Information Science / General.2bisacsh1 aStanding Committee of the IFLA Section on Cataloguing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTask Force on Guidelines for OPAC Displays, , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Law 2000-2014 (EN)z978311062097908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Library Information Science 2000-2014 (EN)z978311062096208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Library Information Science 2000 - 2014z9783110636246oZDB-23-GLI08iTitle is part of eBook package:d